    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-03-19T17:45:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-03-19T17:45:00-05:00" n="401"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d401">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00/5482: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Eberhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-03-19T17:00:00-05:45">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 19, 1928—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 7:11 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>136. With reference to the last sentence of paragraph 2 of the Department’s
                    telegram number 69 of March 15, 7 p.m. [<hi rend="italic">noon</hi>]. It is our
                    opinion that it would not be necessary or advisable so far as we can see at
                    present for the President of the United States to issue the suggested order to
                    General McCoy. The latter now has full and general authority to supervise the
                    election and detailed specific instructions might in his opinion hinder his
                    freedom of action.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Eberhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
